in front of us, there is a group
of ISIS fighters,

29:26.264 --> 29:27.499 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
plus a car bomb.

29:27.532 --> 29:29.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They always try to send car
bombs.

29:29.434 --> 29:35.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: When the fighting
eases, civilians
appear from their houses on the
street outside.

29:35.207 --> 29:40.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One soldier proudly shows us his
loot he's
poached from ISIS: uniforms and
memorabilia

29:40.812 --> 29:43.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the Islamic State.

29:43.415 --> 29:50.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Further down the street, Major
Ziad sees more
ISIS fighters.

29:50.122 --> 29:54.359 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He calls for a mortar strike.

29:54.393 --> 29:57.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
On this tablet, they can
pinpoint targets
in the city.

29:57.696 --> 30:02.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With so many civilians still in
their homes,
there is no room for error.

30:02.868 --> 30:06.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They then race to the rooftop to
get a better
view.

30:06.471 --> 30:09.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The front line snakes through
the streets
around us.

30:09.441 --> 30:14.913 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ISIS fighters can come from many
sides.

30:14.946 --> 30:17.115 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Two mortars hit buildings
nearby.

30:17.149 --> 30:23.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you tell us, what are the
main dangers
in this battle?

30:23.522 --> 30:31.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): The
most dangerous
thing ISIS is using is the car
bomb.

30:31.363 --> 30:35.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Also they have a new style,
using drone-carried
bombs.

30:35.400 --> 30:37.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They can control them with the
remote.

30:37.436 --> 30:39.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They use a small amount of
explosives.

30:39.604 --> 30:43.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They target our cars and groups
of us.

30:43.108 --> 30:50.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: ISIS had two
years to plan
its defense, and the group spent
that time

30:50.515 --> 30:53.385 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
innovating its tactics and
weapons.

30:53.418 --> 30:55.687 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thick armor envelops car bombs.

30:55.721 --> 31:01.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bullets cannot penetrate them,
so suicidal
drivers tear towards Iraqi
fighters, seen

31:01.593 --> 31:08.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
here in an ISIS propaganda
video.

31:08.366 --> 31:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this urban environment, cars
can appear
from around corners just yards
away, so crude

31:14.406 --> 31:18.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
barricades have been erected,
and civilians
banned from driving.

31:18.810 --> 31:25.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If any car approaches, these
soldiers shoot.

31:25.250 --> 31:28.186 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And ISIS is not only deadly
above ground.

31:28.220 --> 31:34.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
An elaborate network of
underground passageways
allow their fighters to creep up
behind advancing

31:34.760 --> 31:37.095 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
forces and shoot at them.

31:37.129 --> 31:40.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hidden below, they can hide from
U.S. coalition
airstrikes.

31:41.032 --> 31:43.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
During the battle, ISIS fighters
wouldn't
just move around through here.

31:43.902 --> 31:46.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They could also live in these
tunnels.

31:46.438 --> 31:49.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can see they have been
sleeping all along
this one.

31:49.274 --> 31:52.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They even have gas lanterns left
and uniforms
here.

31:52.744 --> 31:58.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Digging machines, like this one
captured by
Iraqi forces, are what ISIS is
using to make

31:58.383 --> 32:03.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the tunnels, giving themselves
an advantage
in the urban environment.

32:03.622 --> 32:07.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even after their retreat, ISIS
is able to
inflict casualties.

32:07.159 --> 32:13.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They rig houses with booby-traps
and leave
hidden bombs across this city,
causing devastating

32:13.498 --> 32:17.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
injuries to soldiers and slowing
the army's
advance.

32:17.269 --> 32:21.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Abdullah Ali's job in the bomb
disposal unit
just cost him his eye.

32:21.540 --> 32:26.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A hidden bomb exploded on him
last week when
he opened the front door of a
house.

32:26.311 --> 32:29.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABDULLAH ALI, Injured in Bomb
Blast (through
translator): ISIS planted it in
the house.

32:29.514 --> 32:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I tried to clear the house, so a
family could
return to it.

32:32.584 --> 32:34.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And then I got hit.

32:34.452 --> 32:40.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Outnumbered and
outgunned,
ISIS' bomb-making tactics are a
way to compensate.

32:40.192 --> 32:44.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ABDULLAH ALI (through
translator): Of course,
the ISIS' main plan is to use
bombs and car

32:44.162 --> 32:45.430 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bombs and IEDs.

32:45.463 --> 32:48.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't have military power,
so they depend
on them.

32:48.900 --> 32:55.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: The people living
in Mosul
are also used by ISIS as cover,
around a million

32:55.473 --> 33:00.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are still in the city, on the
front line of
a war that rages around them.

33:00.745 --> 33:05.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And with so many families still
sheltering
inside their homes, airstrikes
risk killing

33:05.684 --> 33:07.452 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the innocent.

33:07.485 --> 33:11.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the Iraqi army battled
ISIS fighters
in these streets, the people
here waited and

33:11.923 --> 33:19.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
prayed for days for it to be
over.

33:19.698 --> 33:22.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This family had been hiding
inside their house.

33:22.033 --> 33:26.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like so many families in Mosul,
they have
found themselves on the front
line caught

33:26.905 --> 33:29.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
between ISIS and the Iraqi army.

33:29.641 --> 33:34.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Food finally arrived with these
government
handouts, and residents poured
into the streets

33:34.713 --> 33:37.115 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to get help.

33:37.148 --> 33:42.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a steady stream of
civilians fleeing
the city, with nothing but
homemade white

33:42.187 --> 33:47.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flags as a flimsy signal that
they mean no
harm.

33:47.692 --> 33:51.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some are loaded onto trucks
bound for refugee
camps.

33:51.263 --> 33:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Others simply walk, hoping to
find help.

33:55.133 --> 33:57.102 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a treacherous journey.

33:57.135 --> 34:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Villages like this outside Mosul
have now
really just become transit
points.

34:02.207 --> 34:07.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Others fleeing from further
inside the city
move through here to make it to
camps.

34:07.679 --> 34:13.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is still fighting ongoing
even out here
on the outskirts of the city.

34:13.818 --> 34:20.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American involvement in this war
is not so
visible in Mosul City, but it is
hugely significant.

34:20.125 --> 34:25.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over 5,000 U.S. troops are
present in Iraq,
training and advising Iraqis.

34:25.830 --> 34:32.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. airstrikes, artillery,
rockets and special
forces are giving crucial
support to the army's

34:32.470 --> 34:35.473 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
advance.

34:35.507 --> 34:40.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In control-and-command centers,
American and
Iraqi military leaders monitor
the battle

34:40.378 --> 34:42.213 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
together.

34:42.247 --> 34:45.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. Army Colonel Brett Sylvia
is the commanding
officer at Camp Swift Base
outside Mosul.

34:45.917 --> 34:47.686 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

34:47.719 --> 34:50.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRETT SYLVIA, U.S. Army: The
progress was
very fast in being able to get
to Mosul, and

34:50.522 --> 34:55.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
predictably, it slows down when
you hit this
dense urban area.

34:55.794 --> 34:58.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, still, every single day,
they make forward
progress.

34:58.930 --> 35:03.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but regardless of how long it
takes, it's
not a question of if Mosul will
be liberated,

35:03.601 --> 35:05.470 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but just a question of when.

35:05.503 --> 35:10.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: The American
military is giving
them as much of a battleground
advantage as

35:10.342 --> 35:16.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they can, but Iraqi soldiers
will still have
to fight their way through the
city's treacherous

35:16.982 --> 35:18.483 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
streets.

35:18.516 --> 35:23.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Men like Major Ziad and his
troops have a
long and dangerous battle ahead.

35:23.054 --> 35:33.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jane
Ferguson
in Mosul, Iraq.

35:33.064 --> 35:43.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now some
lessons from time
spent in space from a man who
seemed like

35:43.274 --> 35:46.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a most unlikely candidate to
become an astronaut.

35:46.811 --> 35:51.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien has a conversation
about a most
unusual career, part of our
weekly series

35:51.649 --> 35:53.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the Leading Edge of science
and technology.

35:53.585 --> 36:03.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Mike Massimino
went to low-Earth
orbit twice aboard the space
shuttle, both

36:03.628 --> 36:06.865 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
times to repair the Hubble space
telescope.

36:06.898 --> 36:12.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In his new book, "Spaceman," he
details the
long and difficult journey he
took to become

36:12.303 --> 36:13.271 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an astronaut.

36:13.304 --> 36:14.439 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, you're afraid of heights.

36:14.472 --> 36:15.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO, NASA
Astronaut: Yes, I
still am.

36:15.407 --> 36:16.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't like this right here,
Miles.

36:16.408 --> 36:17.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm a little worried.

36:17.409 --> 36:19.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You don't swim
very well.

36:19.444 --> 36:20.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: No.

36:21.012 --> 36:23.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The hardest thing for me as an
astronaut was
to improve my swimming skills.

36:23.048 --> 36:25.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Vision was a
problem, a real
problem.

36:25.150 --> 36:26.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Imagine being
D.Q.ed because
I couldn't see well enough.

36:26.651 --> 36:30.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And you barely
got through
the program at MIT.

36:30.522 --> 36:31.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes.

36:31.523 --> 36:32.490 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

36:32.524 --> 36:34.225 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

36:34.259 --> 36:35.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, really, it's
completely
improbable that you became an
astronaut.

36:35.960 --> 36:36.928 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

36:36.961 --> 36:38.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes, yes,
absolutely.

36:38.830 --> 36:41.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: We met beside the
shuttle Enterprise
display at the Intrepid Sea, Air
and Space

36:42.000 --> 36:45.437 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Museum in New York City, his
hometown.

36:45.470 --> 36:50.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It occurs to me, though, that
the lessons
you learned all along the way,
then, dealing

36:50.075 --> 36:54.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- coping and dealing with those
setbacks,
those failures, the resilience,
are exactly

36:55.013 --> 36:57.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what you need to go through to
become an astronaut.

36:57.715 --> 36:58.683 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Aha.

36:58.716 --> 36:59.684 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now we're getting at something.

36:59.717 --> 37:01.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think you're right, yes.

37:01.653 --> 37:06.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not a question of being the
best at something
or things coming easy to you,
but it's being

37:06.724 --> 37:09.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a person that can work with
others and not
give up.

37:09.360 --> 37:12.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, for me, that was part of it
too.

37:12.097 --> 37:16.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At every step of the way, when I
had trouble,
there were people that came in,
in my life

37:16.201 --> 37:18.002 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that helped me.

37:18.036 --> 37:21.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's important to go seek help
when you need
it, and to give help when other
people need

37:21.106 --> 37:22.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

37:22.974 --> 37:26.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that is really more
important than coming
in with a gigantic brain into
the astronaut

37:26.511 --> 37:27.779 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
program.

37:27.812 --> 37:29.481 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: That's an
important lesson
for all of us, I think.

37:29.514 --> 37:31.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: I think so,
especially
when doing things that are
really hard.

37:31.616 --> 37:36.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It occurs to me
that this book,
to some degree, it's about
space, but space

37:36.688 --> 37:39.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is almost a backdrop for a
completely separate
story.

37:39.591 --> 37:40.825 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that the way you view it?

37:40.859 --> 37:42.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: I applied to
be an astronaut
four times.

37:42.327 --> 37:44.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was rejected three times
before I was accepted.

37:44.295 --> 37:47.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's about that, not --
following your
dream and not giving up.

37:47.665 --> 37:51.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: If you hadn't
persevered and
become an astronaut, what would
you be doing

37:51.769 --> 37:53.505 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today?

37:53.538 --> 37:54.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes, I would
probably be
working on my next astronaut
application.

37:54.572 --> 37:55.940 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think -- that's what I think.

37:55.974 --> 37:57.775 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

37:57.809 --> 38:00.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You always made
an effort to
connect with and try to relate
the experience

38:00.712 --> 38:01.679 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to others.

38:01.713 --> 38:03.515 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes.

38:03.548 --> 38:07.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But I don't think
I have ever
heard any astronaut put words to
that experience

38:07.352 --> 38:09.053 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that really do it justice.

38:09.087 --> 38:13.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is it possible to explain
especially what
it's like when you're on an EVA,
on a space

38:13.791 --> 38:14.759 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
walk?

38:14.792 --> 38:15.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: It's very
emotional.

38:15.994 --> 38:17.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the way I try to describe it
is what I
was feeling.

38:17.862 --> 38:21.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And viewing our planet was so
compelling.

38:21.766 --> 38:24.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Words like beautiful and awesome
just don't
do it justice.

38:24.702 --> 38:27.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I felt that I was looking at a
paradise.

38:27.705 --> 38:29.474 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was looking at heaven.

38:29.507 --> 38:35.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can't imagine any place being
more beautiful
than our planet and how lucky we
are to be

38:35.947 --> 38:37.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
able to live here.

38:37.415 --> 38:39.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's what I felt.

38:39.250 --> 38:44.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's what I was thinking at
the time, which
I think is a better way for me
to explain

38:44.289 --> 38:49.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it than trying to think of words
that don't
exist to explain to people just
how beautiful

38:49.127 --> 38:50.094 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it is.

38:50.128 --> 38:51.095 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That's pretty
good.

38:51.129 --> 38:52.096 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Not bad.

38:52.130 --> 38:54.265 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Well, thanks.

38:54.299 --> 38:58.002 align:left position:0%,start line:66.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: There was a
moment on that
flight where you might have
ruined your
stop-and-smell-the-roses

38:58.036 --> 39:00.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
moment, and that was when you
almost broke
the Hubble.

39:00.038 --> 39:01.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes.

39:01.806 --> 39:05.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were trying to do a repair of
the space
telescope imaging spectrograph,
but, before

39:05.143 --> 39:09.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we could do that, we had a very
easy task,
which was to remove a handrail
with big bolts

39:09.747 --> 39:10.715 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on it.

39:10.748 --> 39:12.417 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I went and stripped one of
those bolts.

39:12.450 --> 39:17.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the solution that came up to
take the
handrail off was to see if I
could just tear

39:17.822 --> 39:18.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it of the telescope.

39:18.957 --> 39:20.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't know if that ever would
have crossed
my mind.

39:20.358 --> 39:22.126 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is so counter to the way we
do things.

39:22.160 --> 39:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, luckily, we had smart
engineers that
thought of it on the ground.

39:25.863 --> 39:32.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm inside the Hubble space
telescope doing
this million-dollar repair on
this billion-dollar

39:32.170 --> 39:33.137 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
telescope.

39:33.171 --> 39:35.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Houston, you ready for this?

39:35.740 --> 39:37.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Yes, we're ready.

39:37.575 --> 39:41.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: I grabbed
that handrail
and gave it a couple of tugs,
and, wang, it

39:41.779 --> 39:42.747 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
came right off.

39:42.780 --> 39:43.748 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's off.

39:43.781 --> 39:45.149 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Final thought.

39:45.183 --> 39:47.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Think about how fortunate we
were to be alive
on that day in 1969...

39:47.685 --> 39:48.653 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes.

39:48.686 --> 39:49.654 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

39:49.687 --> 39:50.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: ... they walked
to the moon.

39:50.922 --> 39:51.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were kind of sprinkled with
moon dust,
our generation.

39:51.890 --> 39:53.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes, we were
very lucky.

39:53.591 --> 39:55.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And it inspired a
whole generation
of astronauts of your
generation.

39:55.660 --> 39:56.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Yes.

39:56.661 --> 39:58.363 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right.

39:58.396 --> 40:01.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Do you worry that
young people
today don't have a similar
inspiration?

40:01.099 --> 40:04.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: I talk to a
lot of high
schools students around the
country.

40:04.669 --> 40:07.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They still have that same
interest, but it's
just different.

40:07.138 --> 40:08.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not like we had.

40:08.439 --> 40:10.608 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a way -- what was given to
us, it's different.

40:10.642 --> 40:13.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now we can engage with the
astronauts that
are in space.

40:13.111 --> 40:17.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was the first person to tweet
from space,
but now every astronaut tweets
from space

40:17.548 --> 40:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and does Instagram and Snapchat
and Face -- they
have Facebook going.

40:21.286 --> 40:26.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it's more of a
personal relationship
they have with space now.

40:26.057 --> 40:31.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They see it as more obtainable
than me watching
my superhero Neil Armstrong and
Buzz Aldrin

40:31.229 --> 40:32.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
walking on the moon.

40:32.230 --> 40:33.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's like, there's no way I can
do that.

40:33.765 --> 40:37.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's more engageable,
and it's just
different than what we had.

40:37.235 --> 40:40.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But they still think it's very,
very cool.

40:40.071 --> 40:42.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I don't see that interest
waning.

40:42.140 --> 40:44.175 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I see it -- I see it as growing.

40:44.208 --> 40:46.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: All right, Mike
Massimino,
thank you very much.

40:46.644 --> 40:47.612 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

40:47.645 --> 40:48.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MASSIMINO: Thanks,
Miles.

40:48.646 --> 40:50.281 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's a pleasure.

40:50.315 --> 40:52.150 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Enjoyed it.

40:52.183 --> 40:55.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Online, find a
review of
"Mars," a new six-part
miniseries that premiered

40:55.620 --> 40:58.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Monday on the National
Geographic Channel.

40:58.456 --> 41:07.231 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's at PBS.org/NewsHour.

41:07.265 --> 41:15.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Next: the battle against cancer,
specifically,
gynecological cancers.

41:15.573 --> 41:21.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gwen died on Monday at the age
of 61, after
her fight with endometrial
cancer, also referred

41:21.212 --> 41:23.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to as uterine cancer.

41:23.081 --> 41:28.052 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It is one of several
gynecological cancers
women face that sometimes get
less attention.

41:28.086 --> 41:33.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than 50,000 women in the
U.S. are diagnosed
with uterine cancer each year,
and more than

41:33.424 --> 41:36.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
9,300 die from it.

41:36.361 --> 41:38.062 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Ovarian cancer is better known.

41:38.096 --> 41:43.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
About 20,000 women are diagnosed
each year,
and more than 14,000 die from it
annually.

41:43.601 --> 41:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cervical cancer's death rate has
dropped dramatically.

41:46.738 --> 41:49.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Roughly 12,000 are diagnosed
with it annually.

41:49.073 --> 41:51.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
More than 4,000 die from it.

41:51.142 --> 41:55.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not focused on Gwen's
particular case
tonight, but we wanted to take
this moment

41:55.446 --> 41:59.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to look at the latest efforts to
diagnose
and treat these cancers.

41:59.117 --> 42:05.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Dr. Karen Lu is chair of
gynecologic oncology
at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center
in Houston.

42:05.456 --> 42:08.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Dr. Angela Marshall is an
adviser to the
Black Women's Health Imperative.

42:08.860 --> 42:11.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She is a women's health
specialist in Maryland.

42:11.763 --> 42:16.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Lu, now that we have set the
table a little
bit, let's add a little context
to this.

42:16.467 --> 42:19.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In relation to other cancers,
how prevalent
are these?

42:19.504 --> 42:21.239 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:21.272 --> 42:23.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN LU, M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center: So,
all together, as you said,
almost 100,000

42:23.408 --> 42:26.978 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
women this year will be
diagnosed with a gynecologic
cancer.

42:27.011 --> 42:30.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, importantly, with uterine
cancer, it's
on the rise.

42:30.882 --> 42:34.218 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And put that
in perspective.

42:34.252 --> 42:39.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Compared to -- you know, there's
a horrible
reality in the cancer
marketplace that some

42:39.791 --> 42:43.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cancers get more attention than
others, and
then the more attention they
get, the more

42:43.795 --> 42:45.596 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
research funding they get as
well.

42:45.630 --> 42:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, how do these cancers compete
and fare
when we think about all the
other cancers

42:49.734 --> 42:50.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that are out there?

42:50.735 --> 42:52.503 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:52.537 --> 42:54.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN LU: There definitely is
less attention,
even though there's such a high
number of

42:54.939 --> 42:56.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
women with these cancers.

42:56.808 --> 43:03.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the breast cancer
community has
done a fantastic job about
demystifying and

43:03.681 --> 43:10.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being open about talking about
breast cancer,
about risk factors, about what
early signs

43:10.154 --> 43:12.023 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are.

43:12.056 --> 43:15.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, when we're talking
about gynecologic
cancers -- so that's cancer of
the uterus,

43:15.460 --> 43:21.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the cervix, and the ovaries --
we're a little
bit more maybe perhaps
embarrassed to talk

43:21.065 --> 43:22.867 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about it.

43:22.900 --> 43:29.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that -- that goes towards
individual women
and the impact that that may
have in terms

43:29.240 --> 43:35.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of them thinking about symptoms
that they
may have, and also kind of on a
broader scale

43:35.413 --> 43:42.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of really garnering
interest and
increasing research funding for
the diseases.

43:42.220 --> 43:46.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Marshall,
I have heard
them described as below-the-belt
cancers.

43:46.123 --> 43:50.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is there a stigma attached with
discussing
this openly, compared to, say,
breast cancer

43:50.595 --> 43:52.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which, societally, we seem to
have no problem
talking about?

43:52.563 --> 43:53.965 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

43:53.998 --> 43:55.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANGELA MARSHALL, Black Women's
Health Imperative:
I think there is.

43:55.733 --> 43:58.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, more importantly, I
think this
is a good time to talk about the
importance

43:58.169 --> 43:59.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of women and self-care.

43:59.704 --> 44:04.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And by self-care, I mean the
importance of
getting screening tests.

44:04.909 --> 44:09.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And screening tests are tests
that we do when
people are having no symptoms.

44:09.480 --> 44:15.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when we do mammograms, we're
screening
for breast cancer in women who
have not symptoms.

44:15.386 --> 44:20.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, for uterine and for
ovarian cancer,
we don't have adequate screening
tests for

44:20.791 --> 44:22.560 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
those.

44:22.593 --> 44:26.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So those are tests that rely on
women reporting
symptoms before we do any kind
of workup.

44:26.831 --> 44:29.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I think it's important to
get the word
out.

44:29.667 --> 44:32.169 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think education is extremely
important.

44:32.203 --> 44:36.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People need to know what the
symptoms are,
and they need to know what tests
to be requesting

44:36.741 --> 44:38.509 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from their health care
providers.

44:38.543 --> 44:42.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Lu, is
there a gap in
women seeing symptoms, but not
necessarily

44:42.179 --> 44:44.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reporting them, or not even
knowing that they
are symptoms?

44:44.348 --> 44:45.316 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

44:45.349 --> 44:47.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KAREN LU: I think there's two
gaps.

44:47.184 --> 44:54.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there's a gap where
women don't know
that there are early symptoms of
these cancers,

44:54.191 --> 44:56.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and so don't recognize them.

44:56.727 --> 44:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then there's also a gap when
they report
these symptoms.

44:59.730 --> 45:02.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Sometimes, they can be
nonspecific.

45:02.533 --> 45:08.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And certainly, with ovarian
cancer, women
will present with bloating or
their bellies

45:08.372 --> 45:11.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will be bigger, very nonspecific
pain.

45:11.342 --> 45:19.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, sometimes, physicians will
dismiss these
symptoms and not fully work up
and think about

45:19.050 --> 45:22.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ovarian cancer or other
gynecologic cancers
as a cause.

45:22.853 --> 45:25.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Marshall,
I see you
nodding your head in agreement
here.

45:25.590 --> 45:27.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is this also the case?

45:27.458 --> 45:30.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And does it disproportionately
affect women
of color or in the
African-American community?

45:30.561 --> 45:31.529 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

45:31.562 --> 45:33.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANGELA MARSHALL: It does.

45:33.397 --> 45:36.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, specifically for
African-American
women, it's important to have
health care

45:36.601 --> 45:41.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
providers that we trust, because
there's historically
been some mistrust in the
African-American

45:41.906 --> 45:43.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
community.

45:43.240 --> 45:46.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's also important to have good
access to
health care.

45:46.243 --> 45:51.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's important for to us
have access to
health insurance plans that
aren't high deductibles.

45:51.716 --> 45:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, some women are forced
with making
a decision to put food on the
table vs. paying

45:56.654 --> 45:58.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for expensive diagnostic
testing.

45:58.723 --> 46:01.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, sometimes, it boils down
to an economic
issue.

46:02.026 --> 46:04.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, sometimes,
it's the
infrastructure that's
influencing whether

46:04.528 --> 46:05.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or not they get the care.

46:05.529 --> 46:06.497 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

46:06.530 --> 46:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANGELA MARSHALL: Exactly.

46:08.399 --> 46:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Lu, if a
patient gets
one of these diagnoses, what
should they start

46:11.268 --> 46:13.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thinking about, and how should
they look at
this?

46:13.504 --> 46:14.472 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

46:14.505 --> 46:16.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
KAREN LU: That's a great
question.

46:16.407 --> 46:20.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, there's so much
information available
on the Internet, and we say
that's good and

46:20.911 --> 46:22.713 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bad.

46:22.747 --> 46:27.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do, overall, think it's
important for
women to arm themselves with
information when

46:27.084 --> 46:29.353 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they go seek health care.

46:29.387 --> 46:33.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the second thing is to
really seek
a specialist.

46:33.991 --> 46:41.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are -- we are specialists,
gynecologic
oncologists, who focus on
treating these cancers.

46:41.232 --> 46:48.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's really important that
women who are
diagnosed with uterine cancer,
ovarian cancer,

46:48.472 --> 46:51.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cervix cancer have a specialist
who can take
care of them.

46:51.942 --> 46:55.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Dr. Marshall,
what about
those cases where, if you don't
have the expertise

46:55.946 --> 46:59.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of a Dr. Lu, you don't live in
Houston, you
don't live near a major cancer
center or medical

46:59.750 --> 47:05.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
center, how hard is it for
someone to lobby,
basically, for themselves, or
advocate to

47:05.056 --> 47:07.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
try to get that extra level of
care and expertise?

47:07.658 --> 47:09.393 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

47:09.427 --> 47:11.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA MARSHALL: I think it
starts with having
a health care provider that you
trust.

47:11.929 --> 47:15.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And, so often, we don't,
especially among
African-Americans.

47:15.933 --> 47:21.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think your primary care
doctor is
a great resource, and I think
you should be

47:21.172 --> 47:26.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
